<h3 id="automation">Automation</h3>
<p>We could also automate the program by using crobtab scheduler in Linux. Follow steps below to configure the crontab:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Type <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">crontab -e</code> in your terminal to add a new crobjob</li>
  <li>Specify the scheduler. First, I suggest you to look at <a href="https://crontab.guru/"><strong>here</strong></a> for the detail of scheduler and also the examples</li>
  <li>Open new terminal and find a directory of our <strong>Python3</strong> by typing <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">whereis python3</code>. It must be saved in <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">/usr/bin/python3</code> directory</li>
  <li>Back to the first terminal and type <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">45 16 * * * cd /your path of web scraping script/ &amp;&amp; /usr/bin/python3 'Web Scraping Covid-19 Kompas News.py' &gt;&gt; test.out</code><br />
If you feel a little bit confuse with above command, let me tell you what I know
    <ul>
      <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">45 16 * * *</code> is our schedule. The crontab uses our local time machine instead of UTC. So our program is going to be running at 16.45 everyday for every month</li>
      <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">/your path of web scraping script/</code> must be the directory where you keep the python script. In my case, it is in <strong>â€˜home/covid19 dataâ€™</strong></li>
      <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">/usr/bin/python3</code> is the directory of Python3 interpreter</li>
      <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">&gt;&gt; test.out</code> implies that the file <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">test.out</code> would be created and as logs for the outputs</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Finally, save the crontab configuration</li>
</ol>

